Reports variables that exceed the defined length in characters.
<p>Example (Microsoft SQL Server):</p>
<pre><code>CREATE PROCEDURE test() AS
BEGIN
DECLARE myVarOk VARCHAR(5) = 'abcde';
DECLARE myVarExceeded VARCHAR(5) = 'abcde12345';

SET myVarOk = 'xyz';
SET myVarExceeded = '123456789';
END;</code></pre>
<p>The <code>myVarExceeded</code> variable is defined as <code>VARCHAR(5)</code> but both assigned values (<code>'abcde12345'</code> and
  <code>'123456789'</code>) exceed this limitation. You can truncate assigned values or increase the defined length.
  To increase the length, use the <b>Increase type length</b> quick-fix.
</p>
<p>After the quick-fix is applied:</p>
<pre><code>CREATE PROCEDURE test() AS
BEGIN
DECLARE myVarOk VARCHAR(5) = 'abcde';
DECLARE myVarExceeded VARCHAR(10) = 'abcde12345';

SET myVarOk = 'xyz';
SET myVarExceeded = '123456789';
END;</code></pre>
